Is grade of failure related to class schedule?

Ming Ming Zhang

2019-04-23

Abstract

We would like to discern whether there are real differences between the grade of failure rate of postsecondary students according to their class schedule (4 groups): starting in Early Morning (before 9:50 am), Morning (from 9:55 am to 12:00 pm), Afternoon (from 12:05 pm to 2:25 pm), and Late Afternoon (after 2:30 pm).

We will use a dataset extracted from a database. Our data includes reports for all courses, schedules, and grade reports for the academic year 2016-2017 (Fall, Spring and Summer terms) at the University of Wisconsin - Madison.

By using analysis of variance (ANOVA) test, one can check whether the means across the above 4 groups are equal. However, as the assumptions of ANOVA test for our data are not met, we use the Kruskal–Wallis test. The p-value of the test is less than 0.05, indicating the evidence is strong enough to reject the null hypothesis at a significance level of 0.05. That is, the data provides strong evidence that the average grade of failure rate varies by 4 different class schedules. By using Wilcoxon rank test with the Bonferroni correction, we are able to find a strong evidence of a difference in the means of groups Morning and Late Afternoon.

courses = dbGetQuery(DB, statement = "SELECT c.uuid AS course_id, c.name, s.section_type, s.number, s.schedule_uuid AS schedule_id
           FROM course_offerings AS c JOIN sections AS s ON c.uuid = s.course_offering_uuid
           WHERE term_code = 1172 OR term_code = 1174 OR term_code = 1176")

Note that other type of grades, such as S or U (Satisfactory or Unsatisfactory) and Cr or N (Credit or No Credit) are not considered in here. In order to protect student privacy, average GPA for groups of five or fewer students has been redacted; see the UW Madison registrar. So we make corresponding changes.

grades = dbGetQuery(DB, statement = "SELECT course_offering_uuid AS course_id, section_number AS number, a_count+ab_count+b_count+bc_count+c_count+d_count+f_count AS enrollment, f_count AS fail
                    FROM grade_distributions JOIN course_offerings ON uuid = course_offering_uuid
                    WHERE (term_code = 1172 OR term_code = 1174 OR term_code = 1176) AND enrollment > 5 AND s_count = 0")

We decompose the variable start_time, i.e., starting time of classes in minutes, into 4 groups:

D$Groups = cut(D$start_time, breaks = quantile(D$start_time,0:4/4), include.lowest = T, right = F)

Kruskal–Wallis test

We will compare means across 4 groups, i.e., Early Morning (EM), Morning (M), Afternoon (A) and Late Afternoon (LA) using a single hypothesis test. Let \(\mu_{i}\) denote the mean of grade of failure rate for \(i \in \{EM,M,A,LA\}\). Consider the hypotheses:

  • \(H_{0}\): \(\mu_{EM}=\mu_{M}=\mu_{A}=\mu_{LA}\).

  • \(H_{A}\): The average grade of failure rate \(\mu_{i}\) for some \(i\) varies across some groups.

First, we will try to apply an ANOVA test and there are three conditions we must check:

  1. Independence Our data were not sampled. However, there are not obvious reasons why independence would not hold for all observations.

  2. Constant variance This assumption can be examined by the box plot of grade of failure rate for 2016-2017 across 4 groups. There are some prominent outliers visible in the Morning, Afternoon and Late Afternoon groups. Notice that there are 1400 and more observations in each group.

  3. Approximately normal This assumption fails because there are deviations from normality. The normal probability plots for each group of the data are shown below.

f1 = ggplot(D[D$Groups=="Early Morning",], aes(sample=rate)) + stat_qq() + stat_qq_line() + labs(title="EM")

f2 = ggplot(D[D$Groups=="Morning",], aes(sample=rate)) + stat_qq() + stat_qq_line() + labs(title="M")

f3 = ggplot(D[D$Groups=="Afternoon",], aes(sample=rate)) + stat_qq() + stat_qq_line() + labs(title="A")

f4 = ggplot(D[D$Groups=="Late Afternoon",], aes(sample=rate)) + stat_qq() + stat_qq_line() + labs(title="LA")

grid.arrange(f1,f2,f3,f4,nrow=2)

Since the assumptions of ANOVA test are not met, we will use the Kruskal–Wallis test instead. It can be summarized in the below table.

kruskal.test(rate~Groups, data=D)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  rate by Groups
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 42.858, df = 3, p-value = 2.638e-09

The p-value of the test is \(2.638\times 10^{-9}\), less than the significance level of 0.05. Therefore, we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the difference in the average grade of failure rate varies across some groups. Next we use Wilcoxon rank test with the Bonferroni correction to find which of the groups are actually different.

pairwise.wilcox.test(D$rate, D$Groups, p.adjust.method = "bonferroni")
## 
##  Pairwise comparisons using Wilcoxon rank sum test 
## 
## data:  D$rate and D$Groups 
## 
##                Early Morning Morning Afternoon
## Morning        0.00011       -       -        
## Afternoon      0.05331       0.34476 -        
## Late Afternoon 0.90460       1.2e-08 0.00012  
## 
## P value adjustment method: bonferroni

Note that the Bonferroni correction suggests that a more stringent significance level is

k = 4 # 4 groups

0.05/(k*(k-1)/2)
## [1] 0.008333333

The p-values for Early Morning and Morning, Morning and Late Afternoon, and Afternoon and Late Afternoon, are 0.00011, \(1.2\times 10^{-8}\) and 0.00012, respectively, which are smaller than the Bonferroni correction significance level 0.008333333. So there are strong evidence of differences in the means of grade of failure rates Early Morning and Morning, Morning and Late Afternoon, and Afternoon and Late Afternoon. In particular, the means of groups Morning and Late Afternoon is the most significant one.
